English <i>rimen</i> ‘to compose or recite verses’.","Possibly an altered form of German   Riemer  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":74,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Rymer was born in 1475, in Lambeth, London, England, United Kingdom. He married Eleanor London about 1500, in Lambeth, London, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1550, in London, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1475–1550":"1475–1550","1478–Female":"1478–Surnud","1500–1585":"1500–1585","1500":"1500","1478":"1478","1475":"1475","1585":"1585","1550":"1550","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1549":"1549","London, Middlesex, England":"Lo